  "prompt": "My sibling lives with me and my husband rent-free. What are reasonable expectations from her in terms of household chores?",
  "response": "When a sibling lives with you and your husband rent-free, it's important to establish clear expectations regarding household chores to ensure a harmonious living arrangement. Here are some reasonable expectations you might consider:\n\n1. **Shared Cleaning Responsibilities**: Expect her to participate in regular cleaning tasks, such as vacuuming, dusting, and cleaning shared spaces like the kitchen and living room.\n\n2. **Meal Preparation and Cooking**: If you are sharing meals, it\u2019s fair to expect her to contribute by cooking some meals or helping with meal prep and cleanup.\n\n3. **Laundry Duties**: She can be responsible for her own laundry and possibly share the use of communal laundry spaces if applicable.\n\n4. **Dishwashing**: If you share kitchen facilities, it\u2019s reasonable to ask her to wash her own dishes and contribute to cleaning up after meals.\n\n5. **Taking Out the Trash**: She should help with taking out the trash and recycling, especially if it\u2019s a shared living space.\n\n6. **General Tidiness**: Encourage her to keep her personal space tidy and contribute to maintaining a clutter-free environment in shared areas.\n\n7. **Special Tasks**: If there are larger tasks or special occasions (like spring cleaning), it\u2019s reasonable to ask for assistance.\n\n8. **Communication**: Establish a system for discussing chores, perhaps through a chore chart or regular check-ins to address any issues or adjustments needed.\n\n9. **Flexibility and Understanding**: Remember to be flexible and understanding, considering her schedule and any other commitments she may have.\n\nHaving an open discussion about these expectations can help set the tone for a cooperative living arrangement. It\u2019s also important that everyone feels comfortable openly communicating their needs and concerns.",
